{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> περί-ζωμα</b>, ατος, τό, <br /> <b>girdle worn round the loins,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" PRev.Laws 94.7 (3rd c.BC), 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Romulus” 21 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] (in form περί-ζωσμα), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 7.65, etc.\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; worn by athletes, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.44.1; by priests, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Aemilius Paulus” 33; by smiths, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 4.8.16 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; ἔχειν π. wear <b>the apron</b>, of a cook, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Hegesippus Comicus 1.7: hence οἱ λόγοι σου περιζώματος ὄζουσιν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.182d \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; ἀσκεῖν ἐκ περιζώματος practise an art <b>with the apron on.</b> i.e. <b>merely with the outward appendage of an art, superficially</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “de Dinarcho” 1 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; of soldiers, <b>underclothing</b>, ἐν περιζώμασιν, opposed to ἐν θώραξι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 6.25.3. \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8726","accentedUnicode":"περίζωμα","shortDef":"a loincloth; apron","mediumDef":"a loincloth; apron","stepGloss":"a loincloth","stepTransliteration":"perizōma","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}